title: Quad Engine Model Rocket Fin Can 34mm Tube

description.text:
This fin can supports A10-3T engines and should vent all the ejection gases into the body tube.  This allows you to create a 'hybrid' rocket.  I have known these things to fly straight and far -- there is no flex in the fins so they fly very straight.  This rocket will be featured at the NoVa Mini Maker Faire.  Credit goes to Charlie Seested for doing the 'heavy lifting'.  
Update: Added a BT-55 tube version that will take a single D Engine

comments.text: What could possibly go wrong!?
comments.author: KeeganH

comments.text: Anything is possible.  But I would use something like XTC3D to coat the can and strengthen it.  I would also give it at least 4 coats of paint (which bonds with ABS nicely and adds some structural integrity).  Finally, make connection to the body tube solid.  Don't just glue it.  Use epoxy or something stronger than just plain superglue.  I would also drill a small hole in the side and pass the a Kevlar thread through it and seal the hole with epoxy afterwards.  Run the thread inside the tube and out the top of the tube.  Connect your shock cord there.  All that gas is going to rip a shock cord right off its paper and white glue mount if that's what you normally use.  Another technique is to drill 2 small holes in the tube around where you would normally mount your shock cord and pass your kevlar in (tying a big knot on one end), so that you go through one hole from inside the tube and then out the tube and back in through the other hole.  Put a thin piece of scrap balsa over the holes on the inside to reinforce them.  Glue liberally and let cure at least 24 hours.  Then go fly.  Don't forget to secure the motors.
comments.author: KeeganH

comments.text: You put way too much thought into that. Have you ever tried to synchronize the ignition of model rocket engines. I'll give you a hint, it doesn't work. All four engines will go off a slightly different. You just better hope they're all on before it clears the guide rod.
comments.author: SkyRider

comments.text:
If by ignition you mean the ejection charge, no I would not do that. If I needed that sort of thing, I would have an altitude or timer fired charge like I do on my high power rockets. I have fired clusters of 2, 3 and 4 rockets without issue though. I use a 'clip-whip' to ensure all the igniters (if they are all good) burn together. Now I do agree I've had a dual and triple where one engine doesn't fire at the same time, but it does fire eventually. Now the ejection charges may be microseconds apart, but in a cluster much of what I do depends on the geometry. A cluster of 3 in one line, running D engines would have engines like this:
D12-0, D12-5, D12-0. Then there is only one ejection charge. In the case of this fin can, I might put in 2 Ds with an ejection charge and 2 without. If the cluster of 4 has 3 engines around a 4th in a triangular pattern (1 at each apex and 1 in the middle), then I make the central engine a bigger motor and the other 3 the same but smaller (e.g. A D12-5 and 3 C6-0s). The rocket will fly on the D motor alone and assymmetrical thrust is not as much of a problem (I have confirmed that in some of my larger rockets -- around 4-5ft tall), although the rocket doesn't go as high or make as much noise. It's when you have a large moment arm for any motor that you worry more about one engine misfiring.

description.text:
Building on my first Nerf targets (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2499284), I wanted a vertical (pole) target. My horizontal targets are made to return to vertical after you shoot them. I wanted my pole targets to face you after you shoot them as well, so I designed them with cams so that the weight of the targets will (after a spin or two from being shot at) do just that.

I call this particular set of targets my "Funny Faced Animals" target. Obviously, you could print up Dinosaurs, Pumpkins, Villains, etc. for yours.

Since I wanted these to be strong enough for Nerf Balls, I made the slot that holds the CDs large enough to handle 3 sheets of label paper per side. Trust me, we experimented enough to know that you NEED 3 sheets per side for the Nerf Balls. If you're only using Nerf Darts, you can get away with only one sheet per side.

The stand was made by customizing the Strong Customizable Pole Stand by LKM (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1902885). It's nice and strong. He did a great job on it!

I added a 6 sided dice to this to make it a game. You roll the dice and have to shoot whatever the dice shows. Count your shots. The next person takes a turn. Low score wins. If the loser's score is more than 5, he (she) steps forward one step for the next turn. If the loser's score is less than 5, everyone steps back one step for the next turn. Certainly you don't need the dice, but it is a nice extra. A note on the pictures on the dice. I used the center part of the CD labels that you normally throw away (I don't, I know I can always find a way to re-purpose things). I'll no doubt be adding a 5 sided dice to my original Nerf Targets.

What you see in the picture requires:

  1. One Walmart arrow shaft (I made all the holes .31" in diameter and I say the store because I haven't seen them cheaper anywhere else)
  2. Six Used (preferably) CDs or DVDs
  3. Enough CD labels to put on three sheets per side with the top sheet printed with whatever target you decided upon.
  4. Hot melt glue to hold the CDs in the Nerf Cam T (make sure you put the CDs on the right way and not upside down) and to hold the Nerf Cam B on the shaft (make sure they're all in alignment!)
  5. Three Nerf cam B (bottom)
  6. Three Nerf cam T (top)
  7. One Pole stand all (I included the base and the feet as separate STLs in case you break one ;) .
  8. One Dice (optional)
  9. Target pictures for the CDs (and dice)

--- Assembly ---
1) The holder is designed to have 4 nickels placed inside of it as ballast prior to it being snapped into the base.
2) Remove support material from main blue star and glue thin blue star into main blue star to cover surface that had support material removed.
3) Snap a silver star into each side of the blue star. A few drops of glue could help hold them in place.
4) Slide the assembled star into the two triangles on the top of the base. A few drops of glue would be beneficial to keep it together.

Enjoy and if you print one please post a picture!

description.text:
Scaled version of the Ultimate Sphere Gear. I found the 18 tooth gear did not fit at all when the entire model was scaled 2x. I replaced that gear with a filler piece. The fillers give places to hold the sphere while spinning the gears. They also reduce the likelihood of getting fingers pinched in the gears. You will need: 1x core.
8x 21 tooth c gears.
12x 27 tooth a gears with or w/o spinning detent.
12x plug b.
32x M6x30mm long, Flat Head screws.

I printed all parts in PLA, with 1.2mm shell thickness and 15% rectangular infills. Also be critical about your first layer and retract settings.
Trimming flash off from around the bottom of a bunch of gears is not fun making. Neither is cleaning blobs out of the teeth of the gears. If you have cleanly printed gears and the gear engagement is too tight to spin easily, reprint the core at about 101% size. Alternately, place thin shims (shim washers) of equal thickness under all pieces. Shims should be no thicker than needed, to obtain running clearance.

  • 2S LiIO battery (I use 2 18650 powertool cells, weighs 90g)
  • 4 pcs 9x4.7 gemfan props

The quad is very moderate in power consumption, 5A @ 7.4V for hovering is possible.
With 60g payload (the power meter) I measured 6A.

P.S.  Hahahaha "sports" isn't even close to being a Category choice for things.  'Other' it is!

The .STL file is all pre-scaled and everything, however.
The sketchup file is attached if you like, you should be able to easily expand it to more if you like.  Due to the limitations of my cupcake's build platform I needed to print two of these and mount them separately.

description.text:
This is a simple, imperfect set of printable modifications for the off-the-shelf Miniq XY table (maybe even similar Proxxon XY tables) to enable it to be CNC controlled. These types of XY tables have become widely (and cheaply!) available. This project consists of five models:
-A motor bracket for the X axis
-A motor bracket for the Y axis
-An end-stop mount for the X axis
-An end-stop mount for the Y axis
-A coupler that connects the motors to the table's handles (you'll need to print two of these - one for each axis)

The motor brackets are made to fit NEMA 17 motors. The X axis bracket has two hexagonal holes. These are intended for standard 1/4" hex bolts. These act as anchor points to hold the bracket in place when slid into the XY table grooves. After inserting the bracket (with bolts installed) into the table, I recommend using a large washer and a wingnut to secure the bracket in place. This can be seen in the included images.

The Y axis bracket, on the other hand, has no good direct attachment point. There are two hexagonal openings on this too. These are intended for standard 1/4" hex nuts. A screw can then be fed from the outside into the nut and tightened (on both sides) to hold the motor bracket in place. This can be seen in the included images. Since this part is being held in place solely by the pressure of the screws, you may want to apply some Loctite or something similar to the screws to prevent them from vibrating loose.

The motor coupler has an insert which is also intended for a standard 1/4" hex nut. A short screw can then be fed through it to hold the whole thing in place when attached to the motor. Any sufficiently small screw and nut can be used on the handle end to attach to the hole in the table's handle. I personally used nylon M3 screws/washers/nuts.

The endstop mounts are designed to use the existing screws at the end of each axis of the table. These are designed for lever microswitches commonly seen in 3D printers (widely available on the web). These should screw directly into the small holes on each mount. Similarly, this same type of switches should be mounted on each motor bracket.

I am running my setup with an Arduino Uno with a CNC shield and two NEMA 17 2Amp 59Ncm motors. I'm also using GRBL 1.1.

Introduce what a star is and how it produces light in the sky. Stars are essentially balls of fire. Our sun is the closest star. At great distances stars are faint with some so dim they cannot be seen without a telescope to magnify the light. Magnitude is the term used for the brightness of a star.
Note how people have seen patterns in random positions of the stars throughout history. Astronomers refer to each pattern or group of stars in the sky as a constellation. There are 88 modern constellations as described by the International Astronomical Union.
Hand out the star coins. Note that each point on the disk is a star. The diameter represents the star's magnitude (brightness). Lines between the stars make connections that relate to the name given to that constellation.

Sample Lesson Plan Introduce what a star is and how it produces light in the sky. Stars are essentially balls of fire. Our sun is the closest star. At great distances stars are faint with some so dim they cannot be seen without a telescope to magnify the light. Magnitude is the term used for the brightness of a star.
Note how people have seen patterns in random positions of the stars throughout history. Astronomers refer to each pattern or group of stars in the sky as a constellation. There are 88 modern constellations as described by the International Astronomical Union.
Hand out the star coins. Note that each point on the disk is a star. The diameter represents the star's magnitude (brightness). Lines between the stars make connections that relate to the name given to that constellation.
Explain the story behind each constellation.
Each constellation is numbered for an identification quiz.
Have students arrange the constellations in the correct orientation on the magnet board.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Inspired by the dual Mount of MacNite and the reversed remix of jartz,
I've created this SINGLE e3D Hotend Mount all by myself from scratch.

You can see the e3d cooling fins from the front and you can attach almost any part-cooler in the front!

For cooling the e3d hotend you should use a 40mm fan, giving you more airflow and cooling power than the standard 30mm one!

in total you'll need:

  • 6 m3 nuts
  • 6 m3 25mm screws for the attachment of the hotend, fan and mount itself
  • 40mm fan for hotend cooling

If you've printed yours please leave a picture of yours in the "I've made one" section. :)

*By converting your dual extruder to a single extruder you change your hotend x- Offset.
To get the Center of the Build Plate with the changed hotend position again, you have to change the extruder offset in your printers onboard settings to ~144.5 mm in x-axis direction.
I've simply unpluged everything from the second extruder and changed my onboard printer settings and my simplify3d Slicer to 1 extruder.

Parametric lithium polymer hobby battery carrier and protector.

A LiPoly pack can not only be damaged if dropped onto a hard surface, it can also lead to an explosion and a fire that cannot immediately be put out.

With a single pack, I would just recommend you clean the butter off your fingers. Having to carry multiple packs at a time however is a difficult task, usually requiring a free hard per battery to do it safely.

You can use some thin multi-purpose rope to wrap around the carrier and make a handle.

With Aurarum filament the caddy is incredibly strong with only one perimiter and 25% infill, results with other brands of filament may vary.

I wanted to add a remote for the Canon EOS-M (the original one), which only provides IR remote capability.

The current model keeps every button accessible and functional, including microphones.
The model you can see on the photo has an additional support for a 5mm IR LED to remote trigger the camera. The support is available in the OpenSCAD file, just commented out.

Fully manual

I measured everything with calipers, and made a dozen iteration print for the details. It's a clean-room reverse engineering of the camera important physical feature. Nothing than the actual camera and a quality calipers was used.

description.text:
This is my first own design in Fusion 360. After more than 20 years with Solidworks and a lot of other different CAD programs, I've decided to try Fusion 360 for my private hobby designs using a newly bought CR-10 as my tool.

This design is made to hold a LED bar/strip purchased in Sweden at a chain of stores called "Biltema", expanding over all the countries in Scandinavia.
For those of you not situated in these countries and have a severe craving for this design, the chances of finding the same LED bar/strip design worldwide (but maybe in other lengths), is in my opinion much probable, just make a search on the net.

The 300mm tube was printed upraised in vase mode with the bottom layers removed/inhibited in Cura 2.7

The support got printed flat on it's side with a 27% infill to get a part in PLA flexible enough.

I've tested these parts in PET-G as well and it is actually a better choice if you're comfortable with that material. The flex in a PET-G part feels rather more comfortable when you snap the support in place, but PLA works, just a bit more force required when mounting it to the profile.

The design, when used on my CR-10, is supposed to be used in a hanging position at the top bar, as well in a standing position on the side of the X/Y-table. Suitable for both 2020 and 2040 profiles.

The 90 degree snap design on the support part, was inspired by the this design ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1000002/#files ) made by the Thingiverse profile called "dintid".

Updated: 29/9 - 2017

I'm finalizing this design with some additional tweaks.
Enlarged Hex-pattern to reduce print time and personally I think they look better. As a bonus, the connectors of the original LED-strip manage to get through the hex holes, making it possible to use the pattern as a cable guide.
Talking of cable guide, one is implemented in the lower position making it easier to route the cable nicely along the aluminium profile.

STEP-files attached in the download section for those of you having the need, skill or urge to change and enhance.

Have fun!!

description.text:
This is a remix of the Really Big Light rebar mount adapter. In the north anything we pound in the ground will be frozen in place until spring. Wanting to avoid rebar sticking up out of the ground for the first four months of the year, I decided to find a way to mount my RBL's in a way I could remove them after the holidays.

The mount and base has NPT threads for 1/2" PVC pipe. I bought three pieces of 1/2" x 24" PVC riser pipe, usually found in the lawn sprinkler area of any home improvement store ($1.73 each at Menard's). I used a full length one for the vertical section and cut the other two in half for the legs. With the base legs about 24" wide it's very stable and the pipe threads fit nice and snug into the printed parts.

The top of the bulb is about 38" high. I plan to run the wires inside of the pipes, coming out the ends of the legs.

9/9 - On request, I've added a version of the RBL mount with a slip fitting on top that fits a 1/2" PVC pipe (unthreaded). This can be used to attach an RBL adapter cap, such as https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2053307. To use this you would need to modify the white bracket that is included inside the RBL. You'll also need to drill a hole in this upper pipe to route your wire down through the pipes and out the leg.

Note - don't overtighten the legs into the base fitting; slightly snug should be fine. Tapered threads can put a lot of outward pressure on a fitting and cause it to split along one of the layers.

title: Home Automation Smart Panel running on Raspberry Pi

description.text:
This is frame for the home automation panel I set up with a Raspberry Pi and 7-inch touchscreen.

If you want to make this, all you need to do is set up a raspberry pi, download chromium (or your preferred web browser), and navigate to your action tiles panel.

If you want to mount the screen vertically like mine, then I have made an easier solution than going through the trouble of actually rotating the raspberry's display and touch device. Just use the attached html file and edit it to use your own panel's URL in the "iframe" element instead of mine. This will launch the panel rotated in your browser.

Here's a video of it in action:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iFGmm-ijJvE

Link to buy the screen:
https://smile.amazon.com/gp/product/B01ID5BQTC/

Link to the Action Tiles web application this is running:
https://www.actiontiles.com/

If you have issues getting your pi to use the full touchscreen width, try adding these setting to the /boot/config.txt file and reboot:

max_usb_current=1
hdmi_group=2
hdmi_mode=1
hdmi_mode=87
hdmi_cvt 800 480 60 6 0 0 0

description.text:
Super-simple spool holder I made to use on my RigidBot. Takes one (or multiple) ball bearings and can be used on spools of a variety of sizes. Conical shape ensures a wide array of fitment. Zero supports needed due to design, so single extruder friendly!

Recommendations

  • Use only one ball bearing, mounted at the narrowest part of the cone. Keeps the spool rotating on its own axis that way, and avoids binding
  • Gluestick the bed first, and make sure your prints are releasing correctly. I failed to do this and demolished a print when it refused to let go.

  • Width is now automatically calculated from height, maintaining same pyramid shape while only setting height

title: Project Orion Spacecraft
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Model of the Project Orion nuclear pulse propulsion spacecraft concept from the early 1960s. The spacecraft would have been 10m (33 ft) in diameter and about 49m (160 ft) tall. It would propel itself to extremely high speeds by detonating nuclear bombs and catching the blast wave with the pusher plate. It would be capable of carrying a crew of 8 on a 6-month round-trip mission to Mars (current Mars mission concepts typically call for 9-month one-way travel time). A larger variant could carry a crew of 20 to Saturn and back in just a few years (the Cassini probe took 7 years to reach Saturn).

I printed my model small to match the scale of some other rockets I've printed, but it will print best at a larger scale.
